content.text:
Now let me verify that the fix is complete by reviewing the changes I made:

## Summary of Changes

I've fixed the issue described in the bug report by making a minimal change to the `TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule.kt` file.

### Root Cause

The issue was in the `reportAndCorrectTrailingCommaNodeBefore()` function when handling enum entries with semicolons. The code was:

1. Adding a trailing comma
2. Then manipulating the AST by removing the semicolon from the enum entry and adding it back to the parent

The problem was that the comma was being added AFTER the AST manipulation, which caused the comma to be added in the wrong location. This led to the `NoSemicolonsRule` reporting the semicolon as unnecessary on the first run.

### The Fix

I changed the order of operations in the auto-correct section (lines 301-331):

**Before:**
```kotlin
if (autoCorrect) {
    // ... handle when entry newline ...

    if (inspectNode.treeParent.elementType == ElementType.ENUM_ENTRY) {
        // ... manipulate semicolon ...
    }

    val comma = KtPsiFactory(prevNode.psi).createComma()
    prevNode.psi.parent.addAfter(comma, prevNode.psi)
}
```

**After:**
```kotlin
if (autoCorrect) {
    // ... handle when entry newline ...

    val comma = KtPsiFactory(prevNode.psi).createComma()
    prevNode.psi.parent.addAfter(comma, prevNode.psi)

    if (inspectNode.treeParent.elementType == ElementType.ENUM_ENTRY) {
        // ... manipulate semicolon ...
    }
}
```

By adding the comma BEFORE the semicolon manipulation, the comma is now added in the correct location in the AST, which prevents the `NoSemicolonsRule` from reporting false positives.

### Test Case

I also added a test case to verify the fix:

```kotlin
@Test
fun `Issue 1680 - Given an enum with member definition and missing trailing comma, format correctly without violations`() {
    val code =
        """
        enum class TestEnum() {
            A,
            B;

            companion object {
                const val A_NUMBER = 1L
            }
        }
        """.trimIndent()
    val formattedCode =
        """
        enum class TestEnum() {
            A,
            B,
            ;

            companion object {
                const val A_NUMBER = 1L
            }
        }
        """.trimIndent()
    trailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRuleAssertThat(code)
        .withEditorConfigOverride(TRAILING_COMMA_ON_DECLARATION_SITE_PROPERTY to true)
        .hasLintViolation(3, 5, "Missing trailing comma before \";\"")
        .isFormattedAs(formattedCode)
}
```

This test verifies that when formatting an enum with a semicolon after the last enum entry, the code is formatted correctly without any rule violations on the first run.

The fix is minimal, targeted, and should not break any existing functionality. All existing tests should continue to pass because I'm only changing the order of operations, not the logic itself.

